## üöÄ QUICK START

# 1. Add rules as git submodule (one-time per project):
#    git submodule add https://github.com/yourusername/rules.git .cursor-rules
#    git submodule update --init --recursive

# 2. Copy this template to your project:
#    cp .cursor-rules/templates/.cursorrules_smart_template_submodule .cursorrules

# 3. Uncomment the sections for your tech stack:
#    - Uncomment Python section if Python project
#    - Uncomment TypeScript section if TypeScript project
#    - Uncomment GCP section if using Google Cloud
#    - etc.

# 4. Add project-specific rules in the "Project-Specific Rules" section

# 5. Commit submodule and .cursorrules:
#    git add .gitmodules .cursor-rules .cursorrules
#    git commit -m "Add Cursor rules as submodule"

# 6. Open your project in Cursor and start coding!

---

## üîÑ UPDATING RULES

# Update to latest rules:
#   git submodule update --remote .cursor-rules
#   git add .cursor-rules
#   git commit -m "Update cursor rules to latest version"

# Lock to specific version:
#   cd .cursor-rules
#   git checkout v1.0.0
#   cd ..
#   git add .cursor-rules
#   git commit -m "Lock cursor rules to v1.0.0"

---

## üë• FOR COLLABORATORS

# When cloning this project:
#   git clone --recurse-submodules <your-repo-url>
#
# Or if already cloned:
#   git submodule update --init --recursive

---

## üîß TROUBLESHOOTING

# Rules not loading?
# 1. Check submodule initialized: ls .cursor-rules/
# 2. Initialize if needed: git submodule update --init --recursive
# 3. Restart Cursor
# 4. See .cursor-rules/SETUP_GUIDE.md for detailed troubleshooting

# Submodule empty?
# 1. Initialize submodules: git submodule update --init --recursive
# 2. If still empty: git submodule add --force <rules-repo-url> .cursor-rules

# File not found?
# 1. Verify file exists: ls .cursor-rules/filename.md
# 2. Check spelling of filename
# 3. Update submodule: git submodule update --remote .cursor-rules

# Path errors?
# 1. Ensure using forward slashes: .cursor-rules/ (not .\cursor-rules\)
# 2. No leading slash: .cursor-rules/file (not /.cursor-rules/file)
# 3. Relative to project root (where .cursorrules is)

---

## üìñ DOCUMENTATION HIERARCHY

# This project should follow the 3-tier documentation structure:

# Tier 1: ARCHITECTURE_PLAN.md (strategic, high-level, project root)
#   - Overall system architecture
#   - Major components and their interactions
#   - Technology choices and rationale
#   - Links to Tier 2 plans

# Tier 2: docs/plans/*.md (tactical, feature/area-specific)
#   - Detailed plans for specific features or areas
#   - Each plan paired with TODO list (*_TODO.md)
#   - Implementation phases and tasks
#   - Updated by Cursor as work progresses

# Tier 3: docs/YYYY_MM_DD/*.md (execution, daily work)
#   - Daily work documents
#   - Session summaries
#   - Decision logs
#   - Timestamped: YYYYMMDD_HHMM_DESCRIPTIVE_NAME.md

